DataElement.preferredName: Prior Thiazolidinedione Antidiabetic Agent Administered End Date
DataElement.preferredDefinition: The date on which an observation or an event ended related to antidiabetic agent thiazolidinedione administered previously.

DataElementConcept.preferredDefinition: Earlier in time or order._The act of having given something (e.g., a medication or test)._Any antidiabetic agent with the glitazone (thiazolidinedione) base structure with antihyperglycemic activity. Glitazone antidiabetic agents selectively bind to and stimulate the nuclear receptor peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor (PPAR) gamma. This results in the selective transcription of a number of insulin-sensitive genes involved in glucose metabolism. This eventually enhances insulin sensitivity, reduces insulin resistance and decreases hepatic gluconeogenesis. PPARs function as transcription factors that regulate expressions of genes involved in cellular differentiation, development, and metabolism (carbohydrate, lipid, protein), as well as tumorigenesis; PPARgamma is expressed at high levels in adipose tissue.
